Defendant Terrence A Muller in court with attorney Victoria Mccandless.  Defendant Terrence A Muller in custody.  Taylor L. Kraus appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Defendant changes plea to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Plea questionnaire received and filed. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. Defendant is advised he is a convicted felon and may not possess any firearms. Defendant is advised he is unable to vote in any election until civil rights are restored. Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  Defendant shall provide a DNA sample for the Data Bank.

The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 3 YEARS and 6 MONTHS, with credit for 63 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 18 MONTHS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS.  The defendant is eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and the court did not address if the defendant is/is not eligible for the "Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program".
The Court STAYED this sentence and placed the defendant on probation for a period of 2 YEARS with the following conditions:  
*Serve 6 MONTHS in the House of Correction with huber for work and school (the court orders the defendant be allowed to earn good time credit); 
NO CONTACT ORDER REMAINS.  The court does not order the DV Surcharge.
Defendant to undergo anger management, cognitive intervention and batters intervention program. 
Defendant shall provide a DNA sample for the Data Bank and pay all appropriate costs over the duration of probation failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.
Court ordered defendant to pay all applicable court costs and surcharges over the duration of probation or, if not paid, a civil judgment is ordered.
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm or body armor. Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended and he may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored. 
